Observation Details: After submitting this photo for review, it have concluded that this bird may be a hybrid between the more infrequent Black-capped and common Carolina Chickadees. The following characteristics noted are typical of a BCCH - messier bib/nape and more white on wingbars. I noticed slightly larger size and longer tail that the Carolinas it was associating with. Yet, the lack of much buff on flanks points toward Carolina, and it was remarked to "not have a strong look of a northern migrant". All in all, I am going to leave it as a Carolina Chickadee rather than put it as a hybrid without certainty.

Observation Details: Found by B. Holden and D. Bell near the Sparrow Field (just south) on the east beach around 0640. Struck us as very odd, (colourless, pale, odd GISS) - many photos taken. Unsure of ID at the time. Recent research has strongly pointed to CACH (as suspected at the time). Observed again briefly on 15 May at the very tip. OBRC report in progress. Link will be added here when complete. Some notes:  Wing Length/Tail Ratio - completed by D. Bell with photoshop pixel count. 15 images all indicate CACH. Proves to be a reliable method as known CACH and BCCH photos also measure out as such.   Greater Coverts - Crossley ID Guide states that BCCH has black centres. CACH gray. Bird shows gray.   Greater Coverts - lacking the white edging shown by BCCH. Proven to be strong indicator for CACH.   Bib - highly variable in research (and within the same bird in different postures) - but matches better for known CACH than BCCH  Bill size - bill appears smaller than the norm for BCCH, normal for CACH.   Head - appears small headed (and rounder) than BCCH - especially when compared to photos of BCCH from elsewhere. Much like CACH.   Nape - proven very unreliable field mark. No obvious differences between CACH and BCCH when using photographs.   Tertial/Secondary edging - variable. Matches CACH better than BCCH on our bird.   White on tail - Pyle states this is a BCCH feature, however we have found a large percentage of CACH show this feature - especially in the two northerly subspecies. (Very rare in birds from the southern USA).   GISS - when observed in real life, the bird "stuck out like a sore thumb". Observation on May 15 was with 2 BCCH and it was independently picked out by us, and Alan Wormington who was ~30-40 feet away - as soon as it arrived.   P.c. extima as subspecies by white edges to flight feathers (bold).

Observation Details: One pair of CACH was agitated by the presence of a rat snake in a possible nest cavity. I observed the birds' commotion for a few minutes before coming around the stump and noticing the snake. WBNU and male AMGO also reacted to the snake, and a female RBWO stopped to observe briefly, but the CACH were most perturbed and persistent in focusing attention on the cavity. I have seen DOWO associated with the cavity recently, and the PROW has visited the stump, too. When I passed by again about 15 minutes later, the birds had left the immediate area of the stump but were audible nearby.

The bird would stick its head well down inside the hole (fairly small entrance, it appeared, in trunk) and come out with a beakful of small wood chips, move off a short distance (four or five feet), and discard the material.  Couldn't really tell if the chickadee was actually excavating material from the lining of the cavity, or was just taking loose material laying in the bottom of the cavity.  In any case, seems early for this species to already be involved in nesting preparation.

Found by B. Holden and D. Bell near the Sparrow Field (just south) on the east beach around 0640. Struck us as very odd, (colourless, pale, odd GISS) - many photos taken. Unsure of ID at the time. Recent research has strongly pointed to CACH (as suspected at the time). Observed again briefly on 15 May at the very tip. OBRC report in progress. Link will be added here when complete. Some notes:  Wing Length/Tail Ratio - completed by D. Bell with photoshop pixel count. 15 images all indicate CACH. Proves to be a reliable method as known CACH and BCCH photos also measure out as such.   Greater Coverts - Crossley ID Guide states that BCCH has black centres. CACH gray. Bird shows gray.   Greater Coverts - lacking the white edging shown by BCCH. Proven to be strong indicator for CACH.   Bib - highly variable in research (and within the same bird in different postures) - but matches better for known CACH than BCCH  Bill size - bill appears smaller than the norm for BCCH, normal for CACH.   Head - appears small headed (and rounder) than BCCH - especially when compared to photos of BCCH from elsewhere. Much like CACH.   Nape - proven very unreliable field mark. No obvious differences between CACH and BCCH when using photographs.   Tertial/Secondary edging - variable. Matches CACH better than BCCH on our bird.   White on tail - Pyle states this is a BCCH feature, however we have found a large percentage of CACH show this feature - especially in the two northerly subspecies. (Very rare in birds from the southern USA).   GISS - when observed in real life, the bird "stuck out like a sore thumb". Observation on May 15 was with 2 BCCH and it was independently picked out by us, and Alan Wormington who was ~30-40 feet away - as soon as it arrived.   P.c. extima as subspecies by white edges to flight feathers (bold).

Several chickadees, both adults and juveniles were foraging in the garden. One of the chickadees was busy plucking rose petals off of one of my roses and apparently eating them. I've never seen that before, but it explains why the rose is so ragged. A Common Yellowthroat started harassing this particular chickadee, driving it away from the rose, chasing it through the garden, and finally, the chickadee flew up into an oak tree. The yellowthroat finally flew away into the hedges at that point.

Observation Details: Interesting occurrence! After having filled the feeder and seen the chickadee come to it, I moved to the front yard to look at the lake. In a few minutes, the chickadee followed me, sat on a nearby twig and began calling out loudly to me. I wondered if it was telling me something about the feeder and so I returned to the backyard. Lo and behold! The grackles were at the feeder. The chickadee followed me to the backyard, waited till the grackles fled on seeing me and then calmly flew down to the feeder! Talk about feeder dependent, .....the chickadee has me feeder trained!!!

Observation Details: A strange train of events today. We observed the adult chickadees calling in distress near their nest site a couple hours before this checklist period and did not hear any nestling calls coming from the birdhouse, which concerned me - the first time chickadees nested in one of our houses (that time a bluebird house), the clutch inexplicably died in the nest. No predator marks, nothing. I feared that the same thing had happened to this clutch, so I took the wren house in which they had nested down and looked inside it. Sure enough, at first glance all the chicks appeared dead.... except for one nestling, which, somehow, was still alive! I therefore removed all the dead nestlings (4 of them) and left the one remaining survivor in the birdhouse for its parents to feed. It began to call, the first time I had heard any of the nestlings call that day; possibly it had thought the others were hiding silently from some predator - not realizing they were in fact dead - and had hunkered down silently also. So the parents stopped distress calling and began feeding their one remaining chick, finally! The beginning of this checklist marks more or less the moment the one remaining chick fledged. It fell/flew to the ground (my sister was the one who actually saw it fledge before she alerted me) and flopped its way over to the base of the maple tree in our front yard, which has a large flower bush around it. For most of this checklist period it was under or in that bush or on our front lawn. The parents found its location after some time and continued feeding it. Unfortunately, I don't think that one fledgling made it past the first day; I never heard it any consecutive days. I don't know what effect this will have on the parents - if their clutch in a certain location fails, will they refuse to use that location again? And, of course, the big question remains: why did most of the clutch die in the nest a day or so before fledging? Again, they looked decently healthy when I took them out, as far as I could tell. The nest location is unreachable to any but a winged predator, and even then it would be difficult to reach. Could it be parasites? Something the parent fed them? If it were parasites that killed them, how did the one chick survive to fledging? Wouldn't a parent have realized it was feeding them something poisonous? Supposing it were some pest killer, would that really affect a bird that forages higher in the foliage or at feeders, and not on the lawn where most people spray their insecticide or other pest killers? The chickadees have nested and fledged chicks successfully from our wren house once before - but why did they die in the bluebird house the time before that in a similar manner?

Observation Details: Found by B. Holden and D. Bell near the Sparrow Field (just south) on the east beach around 0640. Struck us as very odd, (colourless, pale, odd GISS) - many photos taken. Unsure of ID at the time. Recent research has strongly pointed to CACH (as suspected at the time). Observed again briefly on 15 May at the very tip. OBRC report in progress. Link will be added here when complete. Some notes: Wing Length/Tail Ratio - completed by D. Bell with photoshop pixel count. 15 images all indicate CACH. Proves to be a reliable method as known CACH and BCCH photos also measure out as such. Greater Coverts - Crossley ID Guide states that BCCH has black centres. CACH gray. Bird shows gray. Greater Coverts - lacking the white edging shown by BCCH. Proven to be strong indicator for CACH. Bib - highly variable in research (and within the same bird in different postures) - but matches better for known CACH than BCCH Bill size - bill appears smaller than the norm for BCCH, normal for CACH. Head - appears small headed (and rounder) than BCCH - especially when compared to photos of BCCH from elsewhere. Much like CACH. Nape - proven very unreliable field mark. No obvious differences between CACH and BCCH when using photographs. Tertial/Secondary edging - variable. Matches CACH better than BCCH on our bird. White on tail - Pyle states this is a BCCH feature, however we have found a large percentage of CACH show this feature - especially in the two northerly subspecies. (Very rare in birds from the southern USA). GISS - when observed in real life, the bird "stuck out like a sore thumb". Observation on May 15 was with 2 BCCH and it was independently picked out by us, and Alan Wormington who was ~30-40 feet away - as soon as it arrived. P.c. extima as subspecies by white edges to flight feathers (bold).
